    .section.section--security

        .section__header

            .section-title Security

        .section__content

            .cards

                .card
                    .card__number 1
                    .card__title Is Strict Contextual Escaping enabled?
                    .card__what
                        .list.list--what
                            .list-heading What?
                            .list-item Make sure SCE is enabled
                            .list-item Use <code>$sce</code> service to explicitly tell AngularJS which content can be marked as safe for a context
                            .list-item As of version 1.2, AngularJS ships with SCE enabled by default.
                    .card__why
                        .list.list--why
                            .list-heading Why?
                            .list-item To deal with content that can not be trusted
                            .list-item With SCE disabled, your application allows a user to render arbitrary data creating security vulnerabilities
                    .card__links
                        .list.list--links
                            .list-heading Links
                            .list-item
                                a(href="https://docs.angularjs.org/api/ng/service/$sce", target="_blank") https://docs.angularjs.org/api/ng/service/$sce

                .card
                    .card__number 2
                    .card__title UI-Router: are private parts of application properly protected?
                    .card__what
                        .list.list--what
                            .list-heading What?
                            .list-item Use border states to protect private areas in your application
                            .list-item Use <code>$stateChangeStart</code> event handler to control access
                    .card__why
                        .list.list--why
                            .list-heading Why?
                            .list-item To restrict access to private areas in your application
                            .list-item To make sure the states cannot be accessed by guessing the url's
                    .card__links
                        .list.list--links
                            .list-heading Links
                            .list-item
                                a(href="http://jvandemo.com/how-to-use-areas-and-border-states-to-control-access-in-an-angular-application-with-ui-router/", target="_blank") http://jvandemo.com/how-to-use-areas-and-border-states-to-control-access-in-an-angular-application-with-ui-router/

